{
  "answer": "**In the introduction to his *Nouveau traité d'économie* (Vol. I, Chapter 0), Charles Dunoyer summarizes his project as follows: \"my design is to show how they [industry and morality] give birth to human liberty.\"**[^1]\n\nThis comes right after he states the \"fundamental truth\" of the book—\"we become *free* only by becoming *industrious* and *moral*\"—and explains that he aims to demonstrate the influence of industry and morality on the exercise of human faculties.[^2] He reinforces this later by describing the work's object as \"to show liberty in its causes,\" presenting it as \"the attribute of his civilization\" born from progress rather than as a dogma or product of government forms.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Charles Dunoyer, *Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL I*, [paragraph](/works/charles-dunoyer-nouveau-traite-deconomie-vol-i-6da8ce/00-introduction/translation/#p-67acca).\n[^2]: Charles Dunoyer, *Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL I*, [paragraph](/works/charles-dunoyer-nouveau-traite-deconomie-vol-i-6da8ce/00-introduction/translation/#p-67acca).\n[^3]: Charles Dunoyer, *Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL I*, [paragraph](/works/charles-dunoyer-nouveau-traite-deconomie-vol-i-6da8ce/00-introduction/translation/#p-2d4253).",
